Strange swan that is apparently a common visitor to the lake and traditionally marked as generic swan species. Perhaps a Tundra/Mute swan hybrid? All white, often held its neck straight, with a straight black bill with yellow lores and pink near the tip. A very slight point where the forehead meets the bill. Very tame, remained calm even when children were running around and ate directly from a woman's hand at one point. Remained at the eastern edge of the dam for most of the time I was there, associating with ducks, gulls, and blackbirds.

Strange swan that is apparently a common visitor to the lake and traditionally marked as generic swan species. Perhaps a Tundra/Mute swan hybrid? All white, often held its neck straight, with a straight black bill with yellow lores and pink near the tip. A very slight point where the forehead meets the bill. Very tame, remained calm even when children were running around and ate directly from a woman's hand at one point. Remained at the eastern edge of the dam for most of the time I was there, associating with ducks, gulls, and blackbirds.

Observation Details: We stepped off the trail to try to get a view of a Nashville Warbler singing in the distance when we flushed this bird from its resting place on exposed granite. It moved a short distance, then held its wings out, almost like a cormorant drying its wings. We approached and it again flushed, this time further and into a more normal resting position. After we got photos, we flushed it once more, at which point it flew a good distance to rest on the branch of a tall tree at the edge of the forest.

Observation Details: I first saw this unusual bird foraging by itself in the back of the southernmost pool, bobbing its tail constantly. When I returned I found it again much closer to the beach hunkered down with many other shorebirds where it gave me great views because it would not move, even when the surrounding flock was flushed by a peregrine falcon.  Shorebird with very dark back with many white spots. Dark cap and eye stripe contrasted sharply with mostly white face, including strong eyebrow. Underparts were mostly white with some smudged gray on the breast. Greenish legs. Bill was slightly lighter at the base, darker at the tip.

It then flew west but reemerged along the other path from the SE entrance, around 37.866834, -122.306984. It then stayed in the same general area, mostly sticking to the fences and weeds immediately next to them.  Very small, bright warbler. Blue grayish on top, white with a warm wash below. Noticeable light fuzzy eye ring. No wing bars. Rusty rump was difficult to see in the field but comes through in photos. The bird didn't seem very skulky. Often by itself but occasionally found with sparrows or Bushtits. Seemed to associate closely with Field Wormweed which can be seen in all of my photos.

Media notes: Encounter 3
Observation Details: Dull bird in fennel in north/nw part of park. Still not certain on species but here are my thoughts based on the distinguishing characteristics listed by Kaufman in Field Guide to Advanced Birding. Crown: Brown with streaking and weak median stripe seems inconclusive for either Brewer's or Clay-colored but probably leaning Brewer's. Supercilium: Grayish, supporting Brewer's, but obviously distinct from crown and eye line, supporting Clay-colored. Doesn't appear to be invaded by streaking but edges don't appear to be very neat, so probably more leaning Brewer's. Malar: Dark lateral throat stripe with white submoustachial stripe point towards Clay-colored, maybe the strongest feature leaning in that direction. Neck and nape: Appears clean gray and contrasting with back crown color, supporting Clay-colored. However, in photos by other birders it looks like there is streaking on the back of the nape which points to Brewer's. Breast color: Appears grayish with no buffy tones, supporting Brewer's. Ear coverts: Strongly bordered not ruling out either species.  I think there was just one bird, but there might have been two. I encountered the bird(s) three times. Description in images indicate which encounter they are from.

Update: After hearing feedback from several other birders, it seems clear that this bird is a Red-naped X Red-breasted Sapsucker.  Continuing since this morning in the same berry tree above Phillip's loop trail. Thanks Jim!  The bird's preferred tree actually appears to be a berry tree growing with a bay tree, creating some confusion. It has sapsucker wells in it which should help identify it.  The bird's plumage is pretty messy and I'm not sure of its identification. It clearly has a strong black and white facial pattern and a black bib, so it's not a pure Red-breasted Sapsucker. But the red crown and nape are extensive and blend with only a hint of black separating them, and there's a bit of red wash below the black bib. The red throat also appears to have a faint black outline all the way around it, which is a strike against pure Red-naped Sapsucker. Perhaps it's a Red-naped X Red-breasted hybrid? Or maybe it's just a juvenile male Red-naped molting into adult plumage and therefore looking a little scruffy. I'd love to hear thoughts from other folks.

Immature bird with all black bill, mostly white head with dark markings around the eyes, smudging on sides of neck, and long dark primaries. Appears different from the bird seen by Alex, Lucas, Mark, and Jim on 12/30 and 12/31.

Media notes: Encounter 3
Observation Details: Dull bird in fennel in north/nw part of park. Still not certain on species but here are my thoughts based on the distinguishing characteristics listed by Kaufman in Field Guide to Advanced Birding. Crown: Brown with streaking and weak median stripe seems inconclusive for either Brewer's or Clay-colored but probably leaning Brewer's. Supercilium: Grayish, supporting Brewer's, but obviously distinct from crown and eye line, supporting Clay-colored. Doesn't appear to be invaded by streaking but edges don't appear to be very neat, so probably more leaning Brewer's. Malar: Dark lateral throat stripe with white submoustachial stripe point towards Clay-colored, maybe the strongest feature leaning in that direction. Neck and nape: Appears clean gray and contrasting with back crown color, supporting Clay-colored. However, in photos by other birders it looks like there is streaking on the back of the nape which points to Brewer's. Breast color: Appears grayish with no buffy tones, supporting Brewer's. Ear coverts: Strongly bordered not ruling out either species.  I think there was just one bird, but there might have been two. I encountered the bird(s) three times. Description in images indicate which encounter they are from.

Found earlier in the morning by Phred Benham. Sparrow-like bird with dark streaked flanks and strong facial pattern featuring an eye ring and a white mustache stripe. Most striking characteristic was the large white stripe on the wing.

Photos by Rudyard Wallen. Medium sized, slender bird seen perched on top of a tree in bad light for about a minute before it flew off to the northwest. All gray with white wing patches seen in flight. Strong oval eye ring and distinct undertail pattern.

Locality: West County Wastewater District--Sewage Ponds (Richmond WTP)
Observation Details: Continuing bird found yesterday. On southern bank of middle eastern pond with Killdeer and Yellowlegs. Medium sized shorebird (slightly smaller than Killdeer) with yellow legs, overall brown color, dense barring on breast abruptly ending at belly with a point, long neck and upright posture.
Female roosting with gulls.
Continuing at stakeout location. Dark, unstreaked sparrow with white facial stripes.

Continuing at the pond visible from the community garden. Thanks to Dominik and Dan for helping me get on the bird, which stayed on the water's edge the whole time I watched it. Peep with mostly clean white underparts, scaly back lacking rufous, dark legs, strong supercilium, and stubby bill.
Female working a stand of dead trees about .1 mile up from the trail head. Couldn't relocate on the way back to the parking lot.
Flyover near Kaiser peak.
Unusual bird. Almost all white, including most of its head, with a pale orange tail and black edges to flight feathers. Presumably a light morph Harlan's.

Locality: Don Edwards NWR--entrance road (Grand Blvd.) between tracks and gate
Observation Details: Continuing large plover with golden speckled upperparts, black underparts, and white along flanks. Visible from the junction of Grand Boulevard and Los Esteros Road. Foraging alone.
I initially thought this was a Western Wood-Pewee, but after looking at pictures I believe it is a Willow Flycatcher. Note the short primary projection in particular.
Continuing north of the viewing platform. Its wings look pretty ragged.

In the field I was convinced that the pictured bird was the continuing Ruff because it is strikingly gray compared to the other roosting Dowitchers and it has sloppy scapulars with a scaly appearance. I never saw its bill. Now I think it's probably a Dowitcher that's late in transitioning to breeding plumage, especially because of its white supercilium, just barely visible barred rump, and similar size to the birds near it. I welcome feedback on the identification. Either way the bird was along the southern edge of the northern pond, visible from the 15mph sign.

Observation Details: Known population of gnatcatchers with all black tails. The males had black caps. A pair were seen along Kiko's trail just east of the trailhead. A single male was also seen near the foot bridges along the trail that starts just north of the bathrooms near Kiko's trail.
Continuing. I only saw a single long-tailed duck at a time but it looks like I photographed two as one has a pink tipped bill.

At one point it flew around for a minute, giving good looks at its all white wings, before returning to the rows of posts.

Continuing. Found after much patience around 100 feet east of the gate to the golf course. Never gave very good looks, but unstreaked breast, plain gray nape, and overall rich brown color noted.
Juvenile flew south after being chased out of the canyon by a Red-tailed Hawk.

I believe this is a juvenile common tern but I'm not confident in this ID and welcome feedback. This was the only tern present. It had a complete dark cap, unlike all of the Forster's terns I had seen earlier in the day whose masks did not wrap around the nape. The front edges of the bird's upperwings are dark. Small black bill. Tail appears all white with a shallow fork. I never saw the bird's leg color.

Continuing bird in northeast corner of the pond. During the brief time I was able to convince my friend to stay it twice appeared on the much discussed pond scum across from the quarry. The lighting was terrible from the north side that early in the morning, but I was able to see its general shape and its tail bobbing behavior, and this embarrassingly bad photo sort of shows the bird's plumage.

While biking to the Golden Gate Bridge we noticed a phalarope in the lagoon southeast of the bridge across the lagoon. Very light, unstreaked back, yellow base of bill. When we returned from the GG bridge about an hour and a half later we couldn't relocate the bird.

It was resting on the small rock to the west of Hermit Rock when we first arrived, where it stayed for maybe five minutes while some friendly birders let me peep at it through their scope. After a bit it took flight, flew around Hermit Rock a few times, then apparently landed high up on the back side. I wasn't able to see it again after that.

Seen in pines on West side of park right next to basketball court. We saw it briefly, then after a long stake out we managed to get decent views of the bird before it flew to the pines near the north entrance.

Male off the northern side near Chimney Rock associating with Surf Scoters. Initially snoozing, later successfully chasing groups of the much larger Scoters.
Continuing in the fennel just south of the soccer fields, found by Noah Arthur yesterday. Bright yellow upper parts, white belly and undertail coverts, eye line and prominent supercilium.

Continuing from yesterday. Flew off to the southeast around 8:45. Before that mostly stuck to the top of a tall eucalyptus tree near where Bill and Vicki found the bird yesterday. Warbler with yellow wash to face, breast, belly, and vent; fine gray streaking on flanks and breast; pale gray mask; and thick white wing bar.

Bright yellow throat and breast, white belly, dull upperparts visible as it flitted through vegetation. I also noticed some white on the face but the markings seemed weak. I ended up getting some terrible photos that show no wing bars and a long tail.

Seen briefly in same area reported yesterday by Rebecca Matsubara around 38.020602, -122.142031. This is just west of the small Granger's Warf parking area. With a couple of White-throated Swifts over cypresses along the western end of Ridge Trail. One of my target species for fall migration here!

Continuing black, white, and red beauty in the oak tree where previously reported, 33.9665774, -118.3402523.

I'm guessing a Horned Grebe? Doesn't really look right for either species. Seen along Shoreline Trail between No Name Trail and Alameda Creek Trail.

Continuing along Alameda Creek trail, found by Derek and Jim yesterday. Small sparrow with clean gray nape and plain breast.  Update from 9/18: After hearing from others and examining my photos more closely, I'm changing this id to Brewer's Sparrow. The bird's markings are very dull, it lacks a pale median crown stripe, its supercilium is grayish with some streaking, and lateral throat stripe is weak.  It looks like this is a different bird than the one Derek photographed, and was apparently in a different part of the trail. But Derek and Jim saw at least two Spizella sparrows, so it's possible that they saw this bird as well.

Confusing matters even more, this bird was singing constantly while I observed it, making me wonder if it could be an oddly colored male even though the yellow suggests that it's a female.
Circling with Turkey Vultures, then flew upstream. Single white band on tail and faint commas on wings rule out Zone-tailed Hawk.
Warbler with gray head, yellow belly and throat, and clean white eye-ring. Flew into eucalyptus for about 30 seconds before flying off.
Found by Mark Holmgren and Dan Fontaine this morning. Only sang one phrase while I was present but gave a few brief glimpses. Vireo with prominent wing bars, yellow wash, and conspicuous light iris.

Difficult to find and see as they were high up in pines and quiet. Only got photos of the female.

With barn swallows circling over the visitor center area. Noted square tail, pale rump, and dark throat in the field. Managed one terrible photo that shows pale forehead and pale breast wrapping around shoulders into a collar.

Continuing bird seen well but briefly in the same area described previously, around 37.909413, -122.331101. Shortly before 1pm one other birder and I saw flashes of an orange face and white stripes down the back. At around 1pm there was a brief but intense downpour which drove away two of the three other birders present. After the rain stopped, the Nelson's Sparrow popped up for nice views of the orange face, gray nape, and white stripes along its back. I'm hoping that the other birder present at this time will post better photos; I only got this single terrible one which shows the orange supercilium, malar, and breast and gray median crown stripe. The bird went down and afterwards we only saw movement as it occasionally darted from one shrub to another.
